.help
For detailed instructions, press the 'F1' (or '?') key at any time.

Partitioning your primary hard disk divides it into a number of partitions
(or "parts").  Each partition can be used for a different operating system.
One partition on your hard will be labeled "Active".  Although you may
change which partition is marked as "Active", the computer will always
boot from whichever one is active when the computer is turned on.

The UNIX System is always installed on the partition that is labeled
Active, which must be at least 60 MBs.  This partition cannot be a DOS
partition.  If you have an existing UNIX System, and you would like to
attempt to preserve the files on the disk, then make its partition Active
but do not otherwise change it.

If you are planning to create a DOS partition, it is recommended that the
DOS partition be partition 1, and that it start at the first available
cylinder on the primary hard disk (usually numbered as cylinder zero).

WARNING:  If you delete any partition(s), all files in the deleted 
partition(s) will be destroyed.
